[SPEAKER_15]: Well, what it looks like is they have what amounts to a 10 foot curb cut.

195
00:15:47,200 --> 00:15:53,223
[SPEAKER_15]: and it looks to be a parking for two vehicles in that access by that 10 foot curb cut.

196
00:15:53,924 --> 00:15:59,006
[SPEAKER_15]: The next eight and a half feet would allow access in to the new parking space.

197
00:16:02,048 --> 00:16:03,789
[SPEAKER_06]: Just to summarize, that is correct.

198
00:16:03,849 --> 00:16:05,290
[SPEAKER_06]: It's about a spot and a half.

199
00:16:05,970 --> 00:16:07,191
[SPEAKER_06]: There's never more than one car.

200
00:16:07,231 --> 00:16:08,832
[SPEAKER_06]: You can't fit more than one car there.

201
00:16:09,872 --> 00:16:15,275
[SPEAKER_06]: So you can only put one car there now and after the proposed curb cut, you can only keep one car there on the street in the future.

202
00:16:18,983 --> 00:16:20,344
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you for that clarification.

203
00:16:20,364 --> 00:16:24,145
[SPEAKER_02]: So you're not removing basically any additional spots to the public?

204
00:16:24,705 --> 00:16:25,866
[SPEAKER_06]: No, we are not, no.

205
00:16:29,667 --> 00:16:43,553
[SPEAKER_15]: And that's why we've been talking about the net gain to the public because there's gonna be no real loss of spots on the street and the gain of taking a car that was on the street off and putting it into the driveway.

206
00:16:47,375 --> 00:16:48,255
[SPEAKER_10]: Andre, please go ahead.

207
00:16:50,104 --> 00:16:50,664
[SPEAKER_08]: Thanks.

208
00:16:50,784 --> 00:16:59,947
[SPEAKER_08]: When the curb cut, the new curb cut is constructed, are you going to reconstruct the sidewalk there and keep it level?

209
00:17:00,547 --> 00:17:03,788
[SPEAKER_08]: Because I noticed that the existing curb cut, you know, it looks old.

210
00:17:03,909 --> 00:17:08,850
[SPEAKER_08]: The driveway kind of merges into the street without much of a ramp.

211
00:17:10,091 --> 00:17:12,031
[SPEAKER_08]: Is that going to be rebuilt, the whole thing?

212
00:17:12,051 --> 00:17:17,453
[SPEAKER_15]: Well, I think whatever measures would be necessary for safety to keep it

213
00:17:18,832 --> 00:17:22,014
[SPEAKER_15]: safe for the public and for the people of the house would have to be taken.

214
00:17:24,295 --> 00:17:29,937
[SPEAKER_08]: I think what's important to us is to continue the pedestrian plan of the sidewalk.

215
00:17:31,112 --> 00:17:33,334
[SPEAKER_08]: Um, so I would want to see that.

216
00:17:33,394 --> 00:17:43,141
[SPEAKER_08]: I'm not a big fan, obviously, of, uh, of permitting kind of new parking in front of homes, but this is a situation where it seems to make sense.

217
00:17:43,161 --> 00:17:44,402
[SPEAKER_08]: It's a two family building.

218
00:17:44,422 --> 00:17:48,025
[SPEAKER_08]: There's only two parking spaces right there and they'd have to be tandem.

219
00:17:48,485 --> 00:17:54,890
[SPEAKER_08]: So, um, you know, so, so I think that I'm, I'm okay with this.

220
00:17:55,070 --> 00:17:59,033
[SPEAKER_08]: I would just like to see the sidewalk rebuilt as part of the curb cut there.

221
00:18:03,949 --> 00:18:15,135
[SPEAKER_15]: Well, again, I think whatever necessary was necessary for the safety would be done, um, in order to keep it safe for everybody as they walk by the area.

222
00:18:16,615 --> 00:18:17,836
[SPEAKER_09]: No issues.

223
00:18:19,357 --> 00:18:20,898
[SPEAKER_09]: Uh, commissioner 40, please go ahead.

224
00:18:20,918 --> 00:18:25,040
[SPEAKER_23]: Thank you, Mr. Chairman.

225
00:18:25,180 --> 00:18:26,660
[SPEAKER_23]: Um, just a couple of comments about this.

226
00:18:26,720 --> 00:18:27,761
[SPEAKER_23]: So, um, first of all,

227
00:18:28,275 --> 00:18:35,358
[SPEAKER_23]: Any sidewalk repair that has to take place or any sidewalk crossing is going to be under the jurisdiction of the engineering department.

228
00:18:35,418 --> 00:18:37,439
[SPEAKER_23]: And so they have a minimum standard.

229
00:18:38,459 --> 00:18:42,801
[SPEAKER_23]: There may be a requirement to replace a good portion of the sidewalk, depending on what kind of shape it's in.

230
00:18:43,782 --> 00:18:55,246
[SPEAKER_23]: In addition to that, I just want it to be noteworthy and made public is that up till recently, the building commissioner would decide the position of curb cuts.

231
00:18:55,506 --> 00:18:56,727
[SPEAKER_23]: And in my opinion,

232
00:18:57,555 --> 00:19:02,920
[SPEAKER_23]: Um, that matter is that that procedure or that order of things is incorrect.

233
00:19:03,160 --> 00:19:13,850
[SPEAKER_23]: Um, you know, it should be up to the building commissioner and his designee to look at the zoning, uh, portion of parking.

234
00:19:13,890 --> 00:19:18,033
[SPEAKER_23]: We really don't have any jurisdiction, um, on public ways.

235
00:19:18,253 --> 00:19:18,654
[SPEAKER_23]: And so.

236
00:19:19,218 --> 00:19:22,143
[SPEAKER_23]: It's not appropriate for us to make that determination.

237
00:19:22,243 --> 00:19:30,155
[SPEAKER_23]: So ultimately, you know, whether the permit comes into the building department or comes in through the engineering department, ultimately any curb cut.

238
00:19:30,656 --> 00:19:46,907
[SPEAKER_23]: decisions or any kind of permits on public ways will now be ultimately decided obviously in conjunction with police engineering and the building department, but ultimately they will have the determination on curb cuts.

239
00:19:46,947 --> 00:19:54,472
[SPEAKER_23]: So that approval will still have to be obtained if the board decides to approve this.

240
00:19:55,433 --> 00:20:00,216
[SPEAKER_23]: The other noteworthy thing I think you should just pay attention to here is this doesn't meet

241
00:20:00,761 --> 00:20:03,703
[SPEAKER_23]: the requirements for a standard parking spot.

242
00:20:03,743 --> 00:20:07,645
[SPEAKER_23]: This is actually the standard for a compact parking spot.

243
00:20:07,745 --> 00:20:28,638
[SPEAKER_23]: And so in my experience, when these things have been approved or let go by a zoning board, it's been my experience that a lot of times, if there are vehicles that are above a compact car or just a normal sedan, it can be problematic

244
00:20:29,673 --> 00:20:40,585
[SPEAKER_23]: in that vehicles do tend to project out into the sidewalk and in the public way, which may cause danger to a pedestrian that's walking by if you force them out into the street.

245
00:20:41,446 --> 00:20:44,150
[SPEAKER_23]: And so I would just recommend that

246
00:20:45,111 --> 00:20:52,020
[SPEAKER_23]: In this order that it be mentioned that this is a substandard parking space, and certainly you know that's fine.

247
00:20:52,481 --> 00:20:59,731
[SPEAKER_23]: There's not a problem with that but it should be mentioned that it is a compact parking space so that you don't end up with a guy like me, who has a truck that's 22 feet.

248
00:21:01,172 --> 00:21:07,295
[SPEAKER_23]: sticking out into the sidewalk, because ultimately that may end up happening if it's not regulated by order.

249
00:21:07,335 --> 00:21:12,778
[SPEAKER_23]: And that'll just give us a little bit more authority when this thing is done and it's paved.

250
00:21:12,798 --> 00:21:20,542
[SPEAKER_23]: And then if we happen to get a call that there's a vehicle sticking out here, then we have a pathway of enforcement.

251
00:21:21,423 --> 00:21:25,706
[SPEAKER_23]: to make sure that any vehicles don't project out into the public way.

252
00:21:25,746 --> 00:21:34,553
[SPEAKER_23]: It's problematic with front row parking, you know, with front yard parking, and that's why it's not allowed by the zoning ordinance because it's extremely difficult to regulate.

253
00:21:34,613 --> 00:21:37,836
[SPEAKER_23]: So I just thought I would advise the board on that.

254
00:21:37,856 --> 00:21:39,137
[SPEAKER_23]: And that's it.

255
00:21:39,597 --> 00:21:39,918
[SPEAKER_09]: Thank you.

256
00:21:39,938 --> 00:21:40,838
[SPEAKER_09]: Thanks, Commissioner Fordy.

257
00:21:42,340 --> 00:21:45,522
[SPEAKER_09]: So just want to double check with the applicant.

258
00:21:46,383 --> 00:21:47,164
[SPEAKER_09]: If the board

259
00:21:48,338 --> 00:21:53,462
[SPEAKER_09]: imposed a condition requiring that this be a compact only space.

260
00:21:55,384 --> 00:21:57,025
[SPEAKER_09]: Is that something you're amenable to?

261
00:21:57,826 --> 00:22:01,289
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes, that is something that would be okay.

262
00:22:02,550 --> 00:22:05,232
[SPEAKER_06]: It will not be a large vehicle there, it will be a compact vehicle.

263
00:22:06,634 --> 00:22:08,315
[SPEAKER_09]: Okay, thank you.

264
00:22:09,156 --> 00:22:16,182
[SPEAKER_09]: So I just wanna, I know Attorney Rapp, you mentioned the prongs, I just wanna double check.

265
00:22:17,485 --> 00:22:21,428
[SPEAKER_09]: We've walked through them and the argument here.

266
00:22:21,468 --> 00:22:35,517
[SPEAKER_09]: So first prong, owing to circumstances related to the soil condition, shape, poverty of such land structures, and especially affecting such land structures, but not affecting generally the zoning district in which it's located.

267
00:22:38,319 --> 00:22:45,104
[SPEAKER_09]: So you have to establish something about the property that requires the variance.

268
00:22:45,144 --> 00:22:54,270
[SPEAKER_09]: So what's the circumstances related to the soil condition, shape, or topography of the land and structures that requires the variance here?

269
00:22:54,991 --> 00:23:06,319
[SPEAKER_15]: If you look at the actual plan that's up on the screen, there's no, as I started when I was saying at the beginning, there's no way to access parking anywhere else on the premises.

270
00:23:07,371 --> 00:23:15,098
[SPEAKER_15]: It is a five and a half foot area on the left side when you face from the street, there's no way to get a car down there.

271
00:23:16,198 --> 00:23:18,781
[SPEAKER_15]: There's also open porches and a shed.

272
00:23:19,341 --> 00:23:22,684
[SPEAKER_15]: So the only place to put that parking is in the front.

273
00:23:23,284 --> 00:23:32,112
[SPEAKER_15]: So that becomes the issue with the structure in the topography.

274
00:23:33,354 --> 00:23:34,354
[SPEAKER_09]: Okay, got it.

275
00:23:34,674 --> 00:23:43,837
[SPEAKER_09]: So size and position of the structure limit the possible locations for an additional parking space.

276
00:23:44,077 --> 00:23:44,898
[SPEAKER_10]: Okay, that is correct.

277
00:23:45,098 --> 00:23:52,800
[SPEAKER_09]: And then the next one is a literal enforcement of the provisions of the ordinance or bylaw would involve substantial hardship, financial or otherwise to the petitioner.

278
00:23:52,900 --> 00:23:55,261
[SPEAKER_09]: So what's the hardship?

279
00:23:56,140 --> 00:23:56,921
[SPEAKER_15]: in this case?

280
00:23:57,461 --> 00:24:05,167
[SPEAKER_15]: It's extremely difficult with respect to parking to find that third space for the structure, for the dwelling.

281
00:24:05,647 --> 00:24:10,731
[SPEAKER_15]: The off-street parking is extremely tight and congested.

282
00:24:11,312 --> 00:24:18,077
[SPEAKER_15]: And again, as we talked about, the setup of it is people are parking in front of this driveway.

283
00:24:18,097 --> 00:24:19,718
[SPEAKER_15]: They're extending beyond the curb cut.

284
00:24:20,279 --> 00:24:21,700
[SPEAKER_15]: That is creating an unsafe

285
00:24:22,739 --> 00:24:28,142
[SPEAKER_15]: condition for Mr. Musi and the occupants of his dwelling when they have to leave the property.

286
00:24:28,582 --> 00:24:32,204
[SPEAKER_15]: It doesn't leave them any room to really move laterally left or right.

287
00:24:32,705 --> 00:24:38,248
[SPEAKER_15]: So that is an extreme hardship for him and people who park in his dwelling.

288
00:24:39,047 --> 00:24:39,267
[SPEAKER_09]: Okay.

289
00:24:39,767 --> 00:24:49,954
[SPEAKER_09]: And then the last one is desirable relief may be granted without substantial detriment to the public good and without nullifying or substantially derogating from the intent or purpose of the ordinance or bylaw.

290
00:24:49,974 --> 00:25:06,384
[SPEAKER_09]: So if I understood your presentation earlier correctly, it doesn't actually remove a street parking space and it's closer to conforming with the zoning ordinance.

291
00:25:06,424 --> 00:25:08,585
[SPEAKER_09]: Is that kind of the high level argument for that one?

292
00:25:08,925 --> 00:25:11,906
[SPEAKER_15]: Yes, that is exactly the situation.

293
00:25:12,586 --> 00:25:14,186
[SPEAKER_09]: Okay, great.

294
00:25:15,187 --> 00:25:19,468
[SPEAKER_09]: Any other questions from the board before we open for public comment?

295
00:25:22,048 --> 00:25:23,168
[SPEAKER_02]: I have one more question.

296
00:25:24,729 --> 00:25:37,852
[SPEAKER_02]: If you open it up, it's not possible for the car to be parked, because right now they'd be parallel spots, but you couldn't put a car

297
00:25:40,617 --> 00:25:44,098
[SPEAKER_02]: the other way, parallel to the street, correct?

298
00:25:44,158 --> 00:25:49,299
[SPEAKER_02]: Like, could we write to make sure that doesn't happen?

299
00:25:51,479 --> 00:25:59,861
[SPEAKER_02]: Even if someone just, you know, oh, I'm moving, let's put it this way so that it's easier to, you know, access the front door.

300
00:26:00,761 --> 00:26:07,102
[SPEAKER_02]: Just because I noticed that the whole, right, it's already paved, it already has the pavers, like, I could see easily that folks could

301
00:26:08,957 --> 00:26:09,738
[SPEAKER_15]: could do that?

302
00:26:10,318 --> 00:26:13,961
[SPEAKER_15]: It would have to be a vertical space coming in.

303
00:26:14,461 --> 00:26:24,489
[SPEAKER_15]: The actual horizontal area of the space wouldn't be enough to get a car in sideways, so to speak.

304
00:26:24,649 --> 00:26:28,633
[SPEAKER_15]: It would have to come in from the street and be vertical.

305
00:26:28,893 --> 00:26:29,173
[SPEAKER_02]: Great.

306
00:26:29,313 --> 00:26:30,414
[SPEAKER_02]: Thanks for confirming that.

307
00:26:31,275 --> 00:26:31,555
[SPEAKER_09]: Yeah.

308
00:26:31,575 --> 00:26:36,459
[SPEAKER_09]: And so, Yvette, if I understood you correctly, the question was essentially,

309
00:26:38,051 --> 00:26:47,533
[SPEAKER_09]: It almost sounded like the car would come in the expanded curve cut and actually go beyond the dimensions of the space here.

310
00:26:47,573 --> 00:26:50,533
[SPEAKER_09]: So just sort of be parallel right up by the steps.

311
00:26:50,613 --> 00:26:52,214
[SPEAKER_09]: Is that the high level concern?

312
00:26:56,134 --> 00:26:56,314
[SPEAKER_10]: Or.

313
00:26:57,575 --> 00:26:57,915
[SPEAKER_02]: Right.

314
00:26:58,135 --> 00:26:59,715
[SPEAKER_10]: If that corrects.

315
00:27:00,015 --> 00:27:05,276
[SPEAKER_02]: That they could theoretically, because if there's no grass right there now, there's nothing but pavers.

316
00:27:05,556 --> 00:27:05,736
[SPEAKER_02]: Right.

317
00:27:06,385 --> 00:27:15,411
[SPEAKER_02]: So could someone just slide in and they could obstruct the sidewalk a bit more?

318
00:27:15,492 --> 00:27:18,454
[SPEAKER_02]: And I think that could just naturally happen.

319
00:27:18,474 --> 00:27:22,096
[SPEAKER_02]: So I guess I would like a confirmation that that type of thing doesn't happen.

320
00:27:22,216 --> 00:27:24,878
[SPEAKER_02]: And I don't know if it needs to be written in.

321
00:27:25,098 --> 00:27:25,799
[SPEAKER_06]: That won't happen.

322
00:27:26,239 --> 00:27:29,962
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you for bringing that up, but that won't happen, especially if there's another car on the street.

323
00:27:30,402 --> 00:27:32,364
[SPEAKER_06]: If you pull in like that, you wouldn't be able to get out.

324
00:27:32,764 --> 00:27:33,945
[SPEAKER_06]: So I don't see that being a practical.

325
00:27:35,315 --> 00:27:36,877
[SPEAKER_06]: approach to pulling in a vehicle.

326
00:27:36,897 --> 00:27:39,280
[SPEAKER_06]: But thank you for bringing that up.

327
00:27:40,608 --> 00:27:53,696
[SPEAKER_09]: Yeah, my understanding is that in the event that any property were to park a car in something that's not a spot, that would be enforceable.

328
00:27:53,916 --> 00:28:00,700
[SPEAKER_09]: So as a board, we don't have to contemplate, well, could someone park in a weird configuration?

329
00:28:01,281 --> 00:28:02,682
[SPEAKER_09]: This is the approved spot.

330
00:28:03,302 --> 00:28:04,543
[SPEAKER_09]: Do we approve it, yes or no?

331
00:28:04,703 --> 00:28:06,844
[SPEAKER_09]: So this is a vertical spot.

332
00:28:07,865 --> 00:28:09,146
[SPEAKER_23]: Mr. Chair.

333
00:28:09,186 --> 00:28:09,666
[SPEAKER_23]: Please, go ahead.

334
00:28:10,024 --> 00:28:10,424
[SPEAKER_23]: Yeah, sure.

335
00:28:10,624 --> 00:28:16,868
[SPEAKER_23]: Um, so, um, we would enforce this and I'm sure that we would get a call almost right away on this.

336
00:28:16,968 --> 00:28:23,793
[SPEAKER_23]: If somebody were parked, um, outside of what this space looks like, um, I would imagine that we would get a call and we would enforce it immediately.

337
00:28:23,813 --> 00:28:34,279
[SPEAKER_23]: Um, plus having a, uh, having an order from this board will actually ensure and kind of solidify the fact that this is the only place that would be allowed to be parked.

338
00:28:34,439 --> 00:28:38,782
[SPEAKER_23]: Uh, you know, nothing would prevent you from having lawn chairs out there and sitting out there and have a cup of coffee.

339
00:28:39,296 --> 00:28:41,677
[SPEAKER_23]: you know, but certainly, um, parking wouldn't be allowed.

340
00:28:41,757 --> 00:28:45,260
[SPEAKER_23]: And, um, you know, because we have this controlling plan now, um, even better.

341
00:28:45,280 --> 00:28:46,620
[SPEAKER_09]: So thank you.

342
00:28:47,621 --> 00:28:59,848
[SPEAKER_09]: Um, chair awaits a motion to open the public portion of the hearing, open the public portion of the hearing for the second.

343
00:29:01,709 --> 00:29:02,209
[SPEAKER_08]: I'll second.

344
00:29:03,330 --> 00:29:03,570
[SPEAKER_10]: All right.

345
00:29:03,590 --> 00:29:04,951
[SPEAKER_10]: We're going to take a roll call.

346
00:29:05,732 --> 00:29:06,452
[SPEAKER_10]: Um, a bet.

347
00:29:08,843 --> 00:29:08,963
[SPEAKER_03]: Aye.

348
00:29:09,924 --> 00:29:10,244
[SPEAKER_10]: Jim?

349
00:29:11,125 --> 00:29:11,285
[SPEAKER_10]: Aye.

350
00:29:12,165 --> 00:29:12,546
[SPEAKER_09]: Andre?

351
00:29:12,566 --> 00:29:13,626
[SPEAKER_09]: Aye.

352
00:29:14,547 --> 00:29:14,827
[SPEAKER_09]: Mike?

353
00:29:15,187 --> 00:29:15,307
[SPEAKER_09]: Aye.

354
00:29:15,948 --> 00:29:19,130
[SPEAKER_09]: All right, the public portion of the hearing is now open.

355
00:29:19,450 --> 00:29:26,535
[SPEAKER_09]: If you're a member of the public who would like to speak on this matter, you can use the raised hand feature on Zoom.

356
00:29:26,575 --> 00:29:28,536
[SPEAKER_09]: You can raise hand on your camera.

357
00:29:29,957 --> 00:29:37,042
[SPEAKER_09]: You can email Dennis at dmcdougal at medford-ma.gov.

358
00:29:40,191 --> 00:29:43,972
[SPEAKER_09]: So yeah, please let us know if you would like to speak on this matter.

359
00:29:43,992 --> 00:30:01,938
[SPEAKER_09]: I do not see any members of the public indicating the desire to speak.

360
00:30:05,237 --> 00:30:08,999
[SPEAKER_09]: Chair awaits a motion to close the public portion of the hearing and open deliberations.

361
00:30:09,019 --> 00:30:10,400
[SPEAKER_09]: Motion to close the public hearing.

362
00:30:11,340 --> 00:30:12,400
[SPEAKER_09]: And open deliberations.

363
00:30:12,721 --> 00:30:13,761
[SPEAKER_09]: And open deliberations.

364
00:30:17,063 --> 00:30:18,884
[SPEAKER_09]: Okay, we'll take another roll call.

365
00:30:19,224 --> 00:30:19,724
[SPEAKER_09]: Andre?

366
00:30:19,744 --> 00:30:20,664
[SPEAKER_09]: Aye.

367
00:30:21,205 --> 00:30:21,625
[SPEAKER_09]: Jim?

368
00:30:22,405 --> 00:30:22,545
[SPEAKER_09]: Aye.

369
00:30:22,966 --> 00:30:23,366
[SPEAKER_09]: Beth?

370
00:30:24,526 --> 00:30:24,646
[SPEAKER_03]: Aye.

371
00:30:25,447 --> 00:30:25,747
[SPEAKER_09]: Mike?

372
00:30:26,647 --> 00:30:26,787
[SPEAKER_09]: Aye.

373
00:30:27,788 --> 00:30:31,890
[SPEAKER_09]: All right, public portion of the hearing is now closed and we are deliberating

374
00:30:33,867 --> 00:30:46,703
[SPEAKER_09]: So folks, just a friendly reminder, the three conditions are the ones that went over with the applicant, so there needs to be circumstances related to the soil condition, shape, or topography of the land or structures.

375
00:30:47,546 --> 00:31:02,253
[SPEAKER_09]: literal enforcement of the provisions of the zoning ordinance would involve substantial hardship and desirable relief may be granted without substantial detriment to the public good or without nullifying or substantially derogating from the intent or purpose of the bylaw.

376
00:31:02,293 --> 00:31:04,474
[SPEAKER_09]: So that's the decision criteria.

377
00:31:04,514 --> 00:31:06,815
[SPEAKER_09]: So what do you think, folks?

378
00:31:11,457 --> 00:31:12,638
[SPEAKER_09]: Andre, please go ahead.

379
00:31:15,185 --> 00:31:19,708
[SPEAKER_08]: I agree, I feel like there's no place else to put this parking space.

380
00:31:21,489 --> 00:31:22,609
[SPEAKER_08]: It's a two unit building.

381
00:31:23,009 --> 00:31:28,012
